  "text": "The second term on the right-hand side subtracts the effect of any a priori input associations due to the applied sampling scheme. If inputs are sampled independently, the term vanishes and the conditional mutual information by itself captures the joint effect of X i and X j on Y. Note, the simple structure of equation (2.7) makes it possible to apply arbitrary input sampling schemes, without having to be concerned about statistical independence. This reveals a considerable advantage of the information-theoretic approach over variance-based methods, which are not easily extended to non-orthogonal samples [CITATION_1] .",
